The paper discusses the similarities between learning dynamics in deep artificial neural networks and synaptic plasticity in spiking neural networks, which suggests that it belongs to the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of machine learning frameworks and autodifferentiation methods, which suggests that it could also belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. The paper's focus on learning spatio-temporal representations from spikes suggests that it could belong to the cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) sub-category. The paper's use of user-defined cost functions and neural dynamics suggests that it could also belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. Finally, the paper's relevance to low-power computer vision architectures suggests that it could belong to the cs.SY (Systems and Control) sub-category.
